--- Featured ---

# Flight: A Lightweight, Component-Based JavaScript Framework from Twitter
http://twitter.github.com/flight/

Yesterday, Twitter Engineering introduced Flight. Flight is a lightweight,=
 component-based JavaScript framework that maps behavior to DOM nodes. Twi=
tter uses it for their web applications. Among others, it is based on: es5=
-shim, jQuery, AMD.

# 30 Days to Learn jQuery: A Video Course
https://tutsplus.com/course/30-days-to-learn-jquery/

A course from Tuts+ with one bite-sized video for each day. This is pretty=
 remarkable for free.

# Building Blocks: Reusable UI Components for Firefox OS
http://buildingfirefoxos.com/

Mozilla's Firefox OS is coming along nicely. The UI components are complem=
ented by an app that generates boilerplate and remote debugging.


--- From our Sponsor ---

# Play with 1,000,000 database records from your browser
http://play.wakanda.org?utm_source=3Djavascriptweekly&utm_medium=3Dplaywak=
anda

Manipulate data with pure server-side JavaScript code =E2=80=93 no SQL, no=
 ORM =E2=80=93 on a live beta application. See for yourself how fast and e=
asy it is to use Wakanda: The open source, data-driven platform for Web an=
d mobile apps.


--- Reading ---

# Our First Node.js App: Backbone on the Client and Server
http://nerds.airbnb.com/weve-launched-our-first-nodejs-app-to-product

Airbnb engineering explains how they used Node.js to share more code betwe=
en client and server. That code runs =E2=80=9Con both sides of the wire, s=
erving up real HTML on first pageload, but then kicking off a client-side=
 JavaScript app.=E2=80=9D

# Do You Know When You Are Looping in jQuery?
http://www.elijahmanor.com/2013/01/yo-dawg-i-herd-you-like-loops-so-jquery=
=2Ehtml

Elijah Manor explains the difference between explicit and implicit loops i=
n jQuery. The difference has performance implications.

# Creating an RSS/Blog Reader for Windows 8 using JavaScript
http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/apps/hh974582.aspx

The latest in a multi-part series on building a complete RSS reader for di=
stribution in the Windows Store. Microsoft has placed JavaScript at the he=
art of Windows 8 so it's interesting to see how existing JavaScript skills=
 can be used to gain an advantage with app development there.

# JavaScript is the New Perl
http://ocpsoft.org/opensource/javascript-is-the-new-perl/

# What=E2=80=99s So Great About JavaScript Promises?
http://blog.parse.com/2013/01/29/whats-so-great-about-javascript-promises/

This article explains the appeal of promises, a technique for asynchronous=
 programming.

# Beginner HTML5, JavaScript, jQuery, Backbone, and CSS3 Resources
http://www.elijahmanor.com/2013/01/beginner-html5-javascript-jquery.html

# Keyboard Events in JavaScript Are Broken
http://codeflow.org/entries/2013/jan/30/keyboard-events-in-javascript-are-=
broken/

Current keyboard events can=E2=80=99t be used if you are differently-abled=
; if you try to make an accessible rich internet application; or if you ju=
st have a different keyboard layout. This article explains the problem and=
 a possible solution.

# Getting Started with Anvil.js
http://jcreamerlive.com/2013/01/29/getting-started-with-anvil-js/

Anvil.js is a =E2=80=9CConvention Over Configuration=E2=80=9D (CoC) build=
 system developed by Alex Robson and sponsored by appendTo. Anvil=E2=80=99=
s philosophy is to be a build system that stays out of your way.

#   What You Might Not Know About JSON.stringify()
http://freshbrewedcode.com/jimcowart/2013/01/29/what-you-might-not-know-ab=
out-json-stringify/

JSON.stringify() converts a JavaScript object to a string in JSON format.=
 This blog post explains how it works.

# Making Use of jQuery UI=E2=80=99s Widget Factory
http://net.tutsplus.com/tutorials/javascript-ajax/an-in-depth-review-of-jq=
uerys-widget-factory/

To aid in the process of building widgets, the jQuery UI team introduced t=
he Widget Factory, which removes most of the boilerplate that is typically=
 associated with managing a widget.

# Answering Baranovskiy=E2=80=99s JavaScript Quiz
http://www.nczonline.net/blog/2010/01/26/answering-baranovskiys-javascript=
-quiz/

Nicholas Zakas uses Dmitry Baranovskiy=E2=80=99s JavaScript quiz as a jump=
ing-off point for explaining some of the quirkier parts of the language.

# Instant Form Validation Using JavaScript
http://jspro.com/raw-javascript/instant-validation/

HTML5 introduces a couple of new attributes for implementing browser-based=
 form validation. For browsers that don=E2=80=99t yet implement these attr=
ibutes, we can use their values as the basis of a polyfill. We can also us=
e them to provide a more interesting enhancement =E2=80=93 instant form va=
lidation.

# Introducing Web Activities
https://hacks.mozilla.org/2013/01/introducing-web-activities/

On mobile devices, you can register your app for handling certain types of=
 actions, or specify in your app what kind of actions you need support for=
=2E Web Activities, one of the WebAPIs, enable the same thing for the web. R=
ead the comments to see how Mozilla=E2=80=99s Web Activities are related t=
o Google=E2=80=99s Web Intents.

# ECMAScript 6 and Array Comprehension
http://ariya.ofilabs.com/2013/01/es6-and-array-comprehension.html

Ariya Hidayat explains this ECMAScript 6 language feature.


